There Is No Shortage of Energy; There Is Shortage of Normalcy

Despite increased production of energy from renewable sources, and despite the slowdown in car manufacturing, oil prices are skyrocketing. Even though fewer power plants still burn coal, coal prices are skyrocketing, as well. Natural gas prices, too, are going through the roof, and energy demand seems to outpace supply in every country and in every form of energy. Have Earth‚Äôs energy sources dwindled so drastically in a matter of months? The answer is a resounding ‚ÄúNo!‚Äù There is no shortage of energy; there is a serious shortage of normalcy in human relations. I hope the current crisis will put some sense into humanity‚Äôs insane consumption.
The energy crunch indicates that we are over consuming. We are producing too much, throwing the excess production to the trash, polluting the ground, the air, and the water, and then we are complaining that we do not have enough. It is about as sane as killing one‚Äôs parents and then pleading for the court‚Äôs mercy because I‚Äôve recently been orphaned.
It is time we reconsider everything we produce‚Äîhow we divide production, profits, and goods, which services are necessary and which are redundant, and most importantly, how we treat one another. The goal of this process should be clear to everyone: survival.
There is no ulterior motive, no attempt to dominate or deprive anyone of power or wealth. It is simply that reality is forcing us to take all of humanity and the entire planet into consideration. If we don‚Äôt, our entire civilization will collapse like a deck of cards.
Since we still do not understand it and insist on running things the way we have always been running them‚Äîthrough power games‚ÄîI anticipate a very cold and gloomy winter for the northern hemisphere. The energy crunch will leave many in dark and cold houses; there will be no gas for cars, and renewable energy will not replace traditional sources since there will be little sun during the winter. I hope that at least, it will make us rethink our values. If it doesn‚Äôt, next summer will be even worse than the awful summer that just ended.
I know that many people are counting on the promise of renewable energy to solve the energy problems of humanity. I think they are mistaken. There is plenty of energy, far more than we really need. We could cut emissions by at least half tomorrow. But the more we have, the hungrier we become, so our thirst for energy will never be satiated, and we will never stop exploiting the planet or each other until we reeducate ourselves and start being humane toward each other.
We have been behaving like spoiled brats whose parents buy them whatever they want. Now, our parents have run out of money and our childhood is over. It is time for us to mature and conduct ourselves like responsible adults, caring for all of humanity the way a mother cares for her entire family. If we think like a family, we will achieve normalcy.

Hey! I saw your question, but to answer them the second question needs to be answered first. 

So when it comes to the difference between the two of them you have to look at the form each pathogen comes in. Whether it‚Äôs a live/active version of it or a dead/inactive version of it is something that we have to take note of. This is important because this determines whether or not a microorganism will be able to cause an infection within the cells of the human body. In the case of inactive forms of pathogens, no infection can occur because they simply cannot do anything. Because of the fact that they were genetically modified to be that way, infections which causes replication of viruses to occur, cannot take place. 

Now in the event that a cell does become infected with the virus, the infected cells will send out chemical signals, known as interferons, that not only stimulates them but nearby cells as well to produce proteins that prevent the virus from replicating within them. By doing this, it also helps restrict the spread of the virus before an adaptive immune response takes place. During this time, if there is no existing memory of an infection similar to this, the body sends the white blood cells along with the B lymphocytes (memory cells) to fight against the infection. Once the infection disappears, these memory B cells will then be stimulated to multiply without having to differentiate into plasma cells to provide our immune system a long-lasting memory against a particular disease. 

Now, to sum these things up and to answer your questions, a cell processing the vaccine is considered as a dead/inactive (even weakened) form of a virus. Because of that it is not enough to cause an infection which can stimulate the cells to release interferons and signals to the adaptive immune response. However, a live/active one is more than capable to doing that. As for what stops T-cells from destroying the cell membrane that is processing the vaccine is again because of the fact that the virus form that is being used in that vaccine one that is a weakened, dead/inactivated version of it.

I have four comments pertaining to the presentation of trial methods and results in this video:

1) For the methods explanation, it would be helpful to know the indications provided to the study participants upon receiving the placebo or vaccine itself to control for impact of environmental exposure to the virus (i.e., How do we know the control group was not any more exposed to the virus after placebo receipt than the trial group?). This may explain some of the differences in efficacy by country despite lower dose (e.g., ASTRAZENECA Brazil versus UK arms).

2) It would be helpful to know the number of participants that went onto the placebo versus trial group. Comparison of participants infected would be more fair if presented as proportions, rather than total numbers. 

3) If we take the example of MODERNA data, the rate of severe symptom occurrence upon infection seems to be about 0.16% (30/185) for placebo and less than 0% (>0/11) for the vaccine group. For Pfizer, we are looking at about 0.06% (9/162) control versus 0.13% (1/9) vaccine group. Overall, the evidence presented to support the efficacy of vaccines against the severity of the disease is low due to small number of participants infected upon vaccination acting as an important denominator in the calculation.

4) For ASTRAZENCA, how does the 131 positive cases of infection break-down by control versus trial arms?

Regarding the Biontech-vaccine: how do B-cells get into contact with the antigen since they only start to produce good igG after sensing the antigen with their receptors. It seems like this is not yet fully understood...

Speaking as a microbiologist with some background in immunology (actual immunologists out there, please do correct me if I'm wrong), you are right in that B cells do need to bind to the SARS-CoV-2 spike antigen in order to respond. This was probably left out by Zach because it is a complicated process to go through and I thought Zach did the video justice by simplifying this bit out so that it does not take away from the key message: both vaccines stimulate production of protective antibodies against SARS-CoV-2. 

The jist is there are two (classical) ways that B cells can be activated: T-cell dependent or T-cell independent. T-cell dependent activation of B cells (which most current research seems to suggest) occurs when the right B cells circulating in your blood encounters the antigen (generated in response to the vaccine). When this happens the B cell internalises the antigen and presents it on its own MHC Class II receptors (as Zach pointed out). These are then recognised by helper T cells that have also been activated by the antigen. This mutual recognition of antigens causes the T cell to activate the B cell (the molecular details for this is super cool but its too much detail to go through!). This activation causes the B cell to proliferate and differentiate to plasma cells that will then make the protective antibodies you need to fend off the infection (in other words, the T cells 'help' B cells to activate thus, their name as 'helper' T cells). I should say that this is a general (classical) description of T cell dependent activation for most antigens and I cannot be 100% certain if the same pathway is true for SARS-CoV-2 antigens.

The other pathway is T cell independant activation. As the name suggests, B cells encountering the antigen here, do not require the T cell's help to activate. They jump straight to making antibodies. However, it is often that antibody immunity from this pathway is not particularly robust in comparison to T cell dependent activation. I haven't followed much with SARS-CoV-2 related literature but most research publications that I have encountered suggests that B cells recognising the SARS-CoV-2 spike protein require T cell activation (again, I cannot be 100% certain that this happens in all cases). 

And this is only just scratching the surface of immunology. There is so much out there we don't quite know yet like why do some antigens seem to require T cell activation and some do not? Anyway, I hope this helps!

First of all, there ARE reported animal studies on the safety of these vaccines. Just search for "non-human primates" and "COVID" and "vaccines" and you will find some of these.

Second, those supposed "prior animal studies w/mRNA for other SARS, but the trials failed w/high rates of injury." is a fake talking point. Beyond the fact that those studies were done with inactivated virus as the vaccine (NOT mRNA), those trials did NOT fail. And no, they did not "damaged/killed test animals over the long term". Of course the animals were sacrificed for in-depth study of any pathology, but that also happened to the non-treated group...

Third, we actually do have humans who have "experienced long term use/test of mRNA" - plenty of prior clinical trials for a variety of diseases and also vaccines in which mRNA was used.

And then there's your claim that "absolute being the prime indicator of efficacy". That's a problematic claim - as an absolute risk reduction for e.g. viral infections also should include a time-frame. I may have a 1% absolute risk of getting COVID in a 2-months period, but that risk increases over longer time frames when that viral infection is just allowed to go around. At some point it decreases again, but that's when you've reached herd immunity.

Oh, and a 1% absolute risk reduction means, in this case, millions of people no longer at risk...

How can you prevent virus mRNA not go into nuclear? And how can you prevent virus mRNA and DNA not combine human DNA?

A nucleus is pretty good at keeping things out, otherwise it would be filled with e.g. the mRNA that it creates to produce our own proteins. And the issue is not so much *preventing* RNA being taken up in our DNA, but more the difficulty in getting that recombination. For that to happen the RNA must first be reverse transcribed into DNA (and we don't really have such "reverse transcriptases"), and then there must be enzymes present that cut our DNA and then paste the new DNA in. Some viruses have such enzymes themselves - HIV is the best known one. But most viruses don't.

And yet we can. Because it really does not need to take 10 years. A very, very important reason that it often takes long is all the waiting time between the different phases. Try recruiting volunteers for a trial - and not just six, but hundreds. You'll have to wait until sufficient people have applied who fulfill the criteria. Oh, and you'll likely have to wait until the site(s) where you do your study are done with their other clinical trials that were already planned. Then you get results back, and your company scientists pour over the data to see if your product is good enough to hopefully have such a beneficial effect that it can earn back it costs for development - with a good look at the competition that may already be on the market. Let's say it is - now you need even bigger trials. More delays in getting sufficient volunteers recruited - and since you need many more, you likely need to do this in several different countries. Long discussions about the right read-out to show efficiency, which can be quite tricky for a vaccine when the disease itself is not very prevalent. In that case you may have to wait for a long time to be sure it indeed gives a protective effect (because you cannot challenge people with this virus). An added issue is that you would, with most vaccines, like to have long-term protection, or otherwise it is unlikely to be of societal interest. So, more waiting time to make sure the immune response lasts for long enough.

But this is a different situation, where we not only had little trouble getting volunteers, there also was less concern about having a long-term (years) immune response for these vaccines to be beneficial. It's very much like the influenza vaccines, where *every year there are new vaccines*.

The researchers do not give the participants the virus itself. The participants get the virus in the same way that everyone else gets the virus, by going about their daily lives.

As I understood it:
In the studies, they give (randomly) either the vaccine or placebo to the participants. Afterward, all participants go about their daily lives. 
After some time, they gather data about how many people got infected and how severe their symptoms were. 
If the vaccine does NOT work, you would expect there to be roughly the same number of sick people in both the placebo and vaccine groups.
Instead, you see fewer people with the vaccines that got sick, which means that the vaccines work :)

There are several concerns the general public needs to understand about the 3 main vaccine offerings (the 4th, from J&J is still undergoing review/approvals). First, the Moderna and Pfizer trials cannot be compared with the Oxford/AZ trials.  The Oxford trial was superior in many ways, because it used (a) longer duration for 2nd booster (28d), longer incubation period (14d), and MOST IMPORTANTLY it assessed ACTUAL INFECTION using PCR.

The Oxford/AZ trial actually determined how many participants were INFECTED (whereas the others look only at people who had symptoms -- those other trials likely had many more who were infected but presented with no/mild symptoms). Thus the Moderna and Pfizer clinical trials did not assess the vaccine properly. They left out people who BECAME infected after their vaccine regimen was used.

Given known details about the three vaccines, the Oxford/AstraZeneca vaccine seems best able to stop this pandemic, in the fastest time. Their clinical trial assessed what is most important (true Infection rate) rather than what the other vaccine makers tested ("apparent infection"/only infections that showed symptoms).  If the Moderna and Pfizer clinical trials had tested for true infection rate, their percentages (Efficacy rate) would be significantly lower.  They designed their study using poor-quality methods, which artificially made their effectiveness appear higher.

Other important aspects for the general public:
- DATA VALIDITY & ANALYSIS -- how correctly did these companies conduct their trials & data analysis? Will they release data?
- STABILITY & DURATION OF INNOCULATION PERIOD -- for how long does the vaccine keep us immune? only 8 months?
- SAFETY -- all of these trials were run for shorter durations. We lack long-term data to really assess long-term safety.
- EFFICACY can be measured in many ways (the first method here was not tested, but is the most important)
  -> RATE OF TRANSMISSIBILITY (% of vaccine recipients who TRANSMIT the virus) == vaccine ability to stop spread
  -> RATE OF INFECTION (% of vaccine recipients who become INFECTED) == vaccine failure rate, per person
  -> RATE OF SEVERE DISEASE (% of vaccine recipients who get Severe COVID-19) == disease prevention rate, per person

Would a covid vaccine produce false positives on an antigen test since the mRNA produces the cell surface spike proteins

Those PCR and antigen-based tests are designed to look for the presence of viral RNA or viral proteins in your respiratory swab samples, and the mRNA injection into your arm muscle will not cause a positive result on those tests.

However, the vaccine will lead to the production of antibodies, which will make you test positive on antibody-based tests for COVID-19, after your immune system has had a week or two to build up its response. These antibody tests (blood tests) are not used to tell whether you are currently infected/infectious with COVID-19 and are totally different from the nose/throat/saliva swab-based PCR tests and antigen tests.

I have been following the scientific literature and trying to make sense of the problems. My lack of trust was partly because of the rash way the pandemic was handled.
All we can do is  look at the data. Since the beginning of this pandemic, all governments based their decisions almost uniformly ‚Äì with the exception of Sweden ‚Äì on the advice of a far too limited group of experts, mainly a few prominent virologists and influential infectious disease modellers, well known from previous activities in pandemic planning, e.g. swine-flu, avian flu, Spanish flu. These virologists and modellers argued that SARS-CoV-2 was a completely new virus, highly contagious and deadly to everybody in the population.  They calculate that an
uncontrolled SARSC2 epidemic would infect about 81% of the UK and the US population. Assuming an infection fatality rate of 0.9%, they predicted 510,000 deaths (UK) and 2.2 million (US) deaths respectively, and a worldwide death toll of 40 million (sourced). Thereby they convinced almost all governments to engage in a rigid suppression strategies until a vaccine becomes available.  They were obviously wrong in their models.

The possibility of pre-existing immunity was also not even considered (as was done  in the earlier epidemics like the swine-flu pandemic) For instance, during the swine-flu, the same  modellers predicted 30 million deaths worldwide from a new strain of the A/H1N1 virus, for which most people were thought to have no immunity. They were wrong. A CDC study conducted during the 2009 outbreak reported that 33% of people over 60 had cross reactive antibodies to the 2009 H1N1 strain. Hardly any people above age 60 were afflicted with swine-flu in 2009/2010 and in Germany the death toll of confirmed cases amounted to 258.  That just goes to show how foolish these modellers were but they managed to pedal enough vaccine. Being government and drug company-funded  made them even more suspicious.

Now if we look at the present stats, well see that in the official mortality statistics of the first seven months of 2020, there are some gross irregularities in the patterns of predicted and actually mortality between countries. 

 We most saw  some short term peaks of excess mortality especially in very old people, but for the most part,  the total mortality peaks leveled off quickly and overall the predicted magnitude of excess mortality did not occur (by the end of 7 months). That's when most people relying on natural herd immunity began to wonder what could possibly be achieved with all the sudden stringent measures after were clearly seen a drop in the death rates.  

For instance, in Germany total mortality showed no excess during the first seven months of 2020 compared to the average of the respective time period of 2016-2019.

Serious question for bio ppl,how it that different from the actual virus ü¶† route when it hijacks the cell via mRNA,also can it mess up or alter our own mRNA coding ribosomes,can it produce weird cytokines that cytotoxic T will overreact to,can vaccinated person spread the virus?

I can try to answer some of these. How is it/that (I assume you mean the vaccine) different than the actual virus‚Äôs actions? Well it is quite similar, and that‚Äôs kind of the genius of it. If a person were infected with the virus their cells would indeed be used to make more virus particles. The difference is that the mRNA contained in the vaccine only codes for the S protein, whereas the full blown virus uses our cells to make that protein and several other parts that can then assemble into complete virus particles - which can then go on to infect more cells, and so on, etc. So just stimulating our cells to make the spike protein is a great way to get antibodies made against the virus, while not having to actually have live virus running rampant inside us.

‚ÄúCan it mess up our own mRNA coding ribosomes?‚Äù Ribosomes read the mRNA code/message, and produce proteins from those instructions. The ribosomes will simply translate the mRNA like they would any other messages coming to them. I‚Äôm not 100% on the question here so I hope that answers it.

‚Äúcan it produce weird cytokines that cytotoxic T will overreact to?‚Äù The vaccine itself, the mRNA, does not produce cytokines, rather cytokines are released by the cells of our immune system under certain conditions. The term ‚Äúcytokine‚Äù is a very broad term covering a lot of different molecules, and undoubtably some will cytokine action will happen as a result of vaccination, however this is one of the pluses (and really the entire goal) of a vaccine - you get enough immune stimulation to produce antibodies, but not so much that you would get horribly sick like you would with regular infection, or suffer a ‚Äúcytokine storm‚Äù as we have heard about with COVID and which you may be referring to.

Your last question - ‚Äúcan a vaccinated person spread the virus?‚Äù a great one, and unfortunately no one knows just yet. I suppose until enough people are vaccinated that we can look at the numbers and evaluate if it has curbed the spread, we won‚Äôt know. That is what everyone is really really hoping for, but since it is not known yet, the current advice is to continue wearing a mask/distance/etc even after vaccination (for now). Bummer I know. Hope any of this helps, thanks for being interested and asking! (Note: I have a B.S. in Molecular Bio, and am not an MD or virologist)

Quick question from a fourth year med student: why do the MHC Class I cells that are presenting the S protein not get marked for destruction by killer T-cells?

A third year medical student here. I found this to be an interesting question so I decided to look up an explanation as we're currently studying immunology and microbiology.

Before having any effector functions, a naive CD8+ T-cell needs to be activated by an MHC I expressing cell which displays the (foreign viral) peptide in the MHC I complex. However, the CD8+ activation requires three steps which only a few cell types can provide. Otherwise the naive CD8+ T-cells could be activated by any viral or non-viral antigen in the MHC I complex by any nucleated cell. Just like the CD4+ T-cells the CD8+ T-cells require a costimulatory signal and cytokines for activation on top of recognizing the antigen with their TCR. The only cells which can provide all of these signals are APCs such as dendritic cells. In order for the CD8+ T-cell activation to happen at all an APC such as a dendritic cell itself needs to be infected by the virus or it can have endocytosed viral particles. The ability of some APCs to display extracellular peptides on the MHC I -complex is called cross-presentation. This ability to display exogenous peptides is _required_ in infections which do not target the APCs themselves and in vaccines for the CD8+ T-cell activation.

How I understand this right now is that the viral peptide, such as the S-protein of SARS-CoV-2, is synthesized in the cells which the vaccines mRNA ends up transfecting. Since the vaccination is done i.m., the cells which get transfected are mainly myocytes and keratinocytes. They definitely display parts of the viral protein and its shorter peptides on their MHC I -complexes, but they lack the ability to provide necessary signals for the CD8+ T-cells to activate. So the initial MHC I complex presentation only inhibits NK cells and there are no cytotoxic T-cells which can recognize the new antigen in the MHC I: nothing happens. The viral S-protein has to travel to dendritic cells before any cytotoxic T-cells against it can be formed. The myocytes and keratinocytes will produce the S-protein to be secreted outside of the cell. If or when these proteins end up in the bloodstream, they will be recognized by the immune system (mainly by B-cells and dendritic cells in spleen, I'm guessing). It's also possible that the transfected cells go into apoptosis and the apoptotic bodies with the viral protein can be taken up by dendritic cells and these dendritic cells then travel to a nearby lymph node to display the foreign antigen. And I guess it's also possible for the cross presentation to start directly from transfected dendritic cells but if the vaccine is given by i.m., there shouldn't be any DCs to transfect. With intradermal vaccinations that pathway might work. 

Anyway, in order for the CD8+ T-cells to mature into cytotoxic T-cells, they need to be activated. Activation happens through interaction with an APC. The APC needs to have seen the viral antigen (S-protein) which is synthesized and secreted by myocytes or keratinocytes. It then needs to process it and display the viral peptide in its MHC I -complex, give a costimulatory signal (B7-family + CD28 -interaction) and secrete cytokines to naive CD8+ T-cell attached to it. To make this a little more complex, it seems that activated CD4+ Th2 cells are also important in the cross-presentation pathway by secreting IL-2 and IFN-Œ≥ to the CD8+ -cell as well as somehow activating or helping the dendritic cells with cross-presenting.

From what I was able to gather this pathway of activation and the subsequent clonal expansion of the effector T-cells from the introduction of viral antigens takes days, even a week depending on the stimulus. The mRNA is very transient as the RNA gets degraded quickly after translation. How long this takes exactly with the SARS-CoV-2 vaccine was unknown but protein synthesis tends to be over in a couple of hours. With a large amount of viral mRNA introduced that might take a bit longer. Hard to say exactly.

Going back to your original question: they should be. However, before any effector cells can be created after the antigen is introduced for the first time, the protein synthesis and most likely the MHC I -complex with a viral peptide attached should be long gone from the myocytes and keratinocytes. However, things might be different if the viral material was introduced again with the same method. In the future, the immune system has the ability to recognize the antigen since the once activated CD8+ cells transform into T-memory cells after the contraction. Transfecting your own cells with viral mRNA again might lead to a very different response. They will present the peptide in the MHC I -complex and they should be destroyed by the cytotoxic T-cells. As for how important this effect is I couldn't say. I didn't bother to look it up either.

People need to realize is that there's nothing absolute in medicine or in life. Medical science is not an exact science like physics. There's no vaccine, medication, treatment or a way of life which is completely safe. We can never know how things are going to be but we have a tool to make sure that these things we produce to cure diseases are as safe and effective as possible: the scientific method and rigorous research. I want to emphasize that safety is the primary subject of study in drug development throughout phases 1, 2 and 3.

Getting a therapy is all about the risks of the disease we are trying to cure and the risks and benefits of the treatment for it. As you probably understand, no healthy person will receive chemotherapy as it's damaging to the body but that therapy might save a cancer patient's life since the risks involved have shifted: the cancer is a much greater threat than the therapy for it. A surgeon might not operate on a patient because the risks involved with the surgery are considerable compared to the possible benefits expected from it. You and I probably go out in the winter and risk getting frozen to death each time. Same applies to when you are crossing the road, driving a car on a highway, eating various unprepared foods etc. yet are probably completely unconcerned and even ignorant of the risks involved in our daily activities that you don't even consider them risks. You probably also instinctively adapt and reduce risks in these activities. You put on warmer clothes during cold weather, look both ways and wear something reflective while crossing the road, wear a seatbelt, drive a safe car, don't drive under the influence and adhere to the rules of the road while you drive as well as look, smell, rinse and taste the food you put into your mouth. Same goes for almost all over the counter medications and supplements we take: they all have a plethora of health risks involved but people rarely tend to consider them. People often tend to think these ordinary things are safe and in most cases they would be right. They are relatively safe. It's not likely that you will get injured or even die on a highway accident. However when you compare the risks of driving on a highway to risks of taking a vaccine, there's absolutely no comparison on which is the most dangerous thing to do. Compared to vaccination, not vaccinating yourself could be seen as a risky behavior in most situations.

Living with risks and uncertainty is the nature of our lives whether you are aware of them or not. Only talking about risks is not of use to anybody. Realizing that there's risks involved in everything and medicine tends to take it very seriously by researching and reporting them openly. In the case of contagious diseases the assessment of risks and benefits involved extends further to involve people around us. >what stops the cascade of interleukins
Cytokine cascades have innate negative feedback loops. Some interleukins are naturally anti-inflammatory and stimulate the anti-inflammatory Treg cells, for example. The receptor binding in a target cell tends to lead into a downregulation of the signaling pathway within the cell which it just activated and so on. Of course, in the case of COVID-19, some of the most severe cases are caused by cytokine storm where the system is out of balance for some reason. I'm not going to speculate on the specific mechanisms why that happens to some people.

> how do the T cytotoxic cells know NOT to "destroy" the host cells?

Cytotoxic T-cells need to be activated by APCs by the specific antigen before they have any effector functions on cells presenting viral peptides on the MHC I -complexes. Before they are activated, they do nothing. And they can only be activated via a regulated mechanism through APCs which have met the same antigen before them. So basically you first need to get the antigen into APCs which then can activate the naive CD8+ T-cells. This takes some time, days to even a week. During this time the CD8+ T-cell matures into a cytotoxic T-cell and proliferates. After that it can attack against any cell presenting that specific viral peptide on their MHC I -complex. I would assume that this MHC I complex peptide presentation is long gone with the myocytes and keratinocytes which get transfected by viral mRNA in i.m. vaccination by the time the CD8+ T-cells have matured and proliferated. On a second encounter? They should attack faster. How exactly this works with the vaccines I have no idea (say, you get another shot of this sort of vaccine). I have no idea if it has any relevance in practice even if the idea of your muscle cells going into apoptosis due to viral peptides being synthesized and cytotoxic T-cells attacking them might sound very serious on paper. Then again, some cells are always bound to die if you stick needles and inject milliliters of anything into them. Perhaps someone has good information on this but I'm too lazy to fact check on that right now.
